# Universe MCP integration for Cursor
#
# Universe provides three advisory tools:
#   universe_route_task    — routing decision (which model role for each phase)
#   universe_recall_memory — past observations for the affected code nodes
#   universe_get_skill     — matching skill/recipe for this class of task
#
# How to use the routing output:
#   "premium"   → use your most capable model (configured in ~/.universe/config.yaml)
#   "low_cost"  → use your faster/cheaper model
#   "automated" → no LLM needed (e.g. run tests, linter)
#
# Workflow for every task:
# 1. Call universe_route_task with the task description and affected graph node IDs.
# 2. Call universe_recall_memory to surface relevant past observations.
# 3. If a skill is suggested (skip_planning=true), call universe_get_skill and
#    follow the instruction returned in the skill's "instruction" field.
# 4. Otherwise follow planner_role → executor_role → verifier_role assignment.

# Available MCP tools (automatically registered via .cursor/mcp.json):
#
# universe_route_task
#   Input:  task (string), graph_node_ids ([]string), developer_id, language, repo_id
#   Output: mode, planner_role, executor_role, verifier_role, next_step,
#           skip_planning, template_id, matched_skill_id, memory_hit,
#           reason, task_type, premium_model, low_cost_model
#
# universe_recall_memory
#   Input:  graph_node_ids ([]string), developer_id, task_text
#   Output: JSON array of ranked observation summaries (empty array if no DB)
#
# universe_get_skill
#   Input:  task_text (string), graph_node_ids ([]string), language, developer_id
#   Output: { found, skill_id, name, instruction, trigger_desc,
#             success_rate, graph_overlap, times_applied }
